segments.text: Other big events of the time, describe Silver Taps.
Silver Taps was a very solemn occasion.
They would play the Silver Taps from the perimeter of the dome of the academic building.
And we would all go to the area on the west side of the academic building.

and we would stand in detention and the band would be there and the band would play the Spirit of Aggieland and then the buglers, about six of them, you couldn't see them and they would play that tap and it would just make ripples run up and down your back because it was so
So effective.
Then they'd read the names of those people and they'd play the silver tabs.
Then it would break up and it was just total silence.
You could hear a pin drop right out there.
Thousands of young men standing around.
When it was all over, they'd just break and everybody there would go just in groups right till they're gone.
Mustard.
We didn't have much in the way of a muster for three years, but then our senior year, April 21st, we had some kind of a tape message from General Moore from the building.
From Corregidor.
From Corregidor.
Do you remember where the ceremony was held on campus?
Yes, the ceremony was held on the
north side of Goodman Hall on the steps.
And I remember this thing from the Philippines was replayed right there.
It was all on some kind of a machine.
And we all heard it very well.
And you know, that's about the time of the fall of Corregidor, wasn't it?
April of 42.
just a little before.
Yeah.
Let's see, how often did you go home?
I went home, I came down here in early September and I went home Thanksgiving.
I went home Christmas.
And if I was lucky I got to go home sometime in the spring, but most likely I didn't.
I stayed here for
from the spring break.
We had two breaks.
We had a break at Christmas and then we had a break at Easter.
When you, before you had a car, how'd you get back and forth on those brief trips to Greenville?
Well, I'd go to the corner where the
I guess there's an old Safeway store there now taken over by the county.
It's mental health and mental retardation in Bryan on about 24th Street and Texas Avenue.
If I was going to go to Greenville, I'd pack a small bag.
I'd have my uniform on.
If it was raining, I'd have my raincoat.
And I'd catch a bus to Bryan.
I'd get to that corner where all the Aggies were, and I'd say, what's the number?
And most of the time, it was 170.
169 of them being ahead of me.
That whole churchyard, there's a little church there.
And so what I would do, the first offer I got to get out of Brian, to Hearn, or any Madisonville, or anywhere else, all those I'd take.
Because I was going to sit there a long time.
So sometime going to Greenville, I caught 10 rides.
Norm, what was the average length of time?
To wait?
No, no, from here to Greenville.
Oh, sometime 11, 12 hours.
But sometime I made it in six or seven, just lucky.
Sometime I'd catch a ride and go all the way to Dallas.
Did you normally go to Dallas and then?
Yeah, then go to Greenville.
I could go to Dallas and go down there
around where the bus station was and get one of those cars that would take people for a small amount of money.
They had those in the Depression.
I could go down there and say, I want to go over to Greenville.
And they'd check their little list and say, oh, here we got one that's going to be leaving here in a little while.
And I said, how much?
And they'd say a dollar.
I said, I want to go.
And that car would come by there.
four or five others that was in the car.
So you never put up a sign that said Greenville?
No.
But you always wore your uniform?
Always wore my uniform.
Did you put up a thumb?
Yes.
To show you were hijacked?
Oh yes, I'd ask you to ride.
Did you ever have anything approaching a negative experience with the person that gave you a ride?
No.
Did you know of anybody that ever did?
No.
I haven't heard of any yet.
No, no.
I never had a problem with anybody.
I don't know anybody that ever did.
Now, were other college students hitchhiking as much as Aggies?
No.
No, we had such an edge with the uniform.
That's what I have to say.
The uniform, people seemed not to worry about the Aggies because we had the uniforms on.
And they weren't afraid of us.
In terms of these worldwide events, do you remember any other other than Pearl Harbor and then what followed it?
Do you remember any other events plus good or bad events that startled you and your friends while you were here?
Were you all alert of when Hitler invaded Poland?
Yes.
Hitler's movement through Poland and all of that, we were on the radio all the time listening to that.
It was just a common practice.
And we were very conversant with Hitler's aggression.
So we were right there on the ball on every move that he was making, knowing all along that we were going to end up in the war.
We knew we were going to be in the war sooner or later.
I'm trying to think of any big event that happened in those years, let's see, 38, 39, 40, 41.
Well, I don't think that any worldwide event that I recall.
I remember when the Hindenburg caught fire, but I think that was before I was in A&M.
And I remember the airplane, the B-25, running into Waldorf Astoria, but I was up in New York sometime then, so events like that.
Let's see, what's the final review of your senior year?
Was that all very stirring?
Very stirring, yes, very stirring.
It was, it was real sentimental, emotional.
We had, as you know, we had two reviews.
The senior led the Corps around and then we stepped aside and the junior stepped forward.
If they had boots they put them on and here they go around again and it was really a very sentimental experience.
The court trips were important in those days.
Yes, yes.
And special trains.
Yeah, talk about that.
We'd go to either Fort Worth or Dallas one year and then we'd go to Houston or Waco and they'd bring trains in for Houston or Dallas, Fort Worth, Fort Worth.
And it was about three or four bucks for a round trip from here to Dallas.
If somebody couldn't afford a ticket, well, you know how those seats were pushed together like this and there was an opening under here?
Sometime we had as many as three or four down between those seats, backs of the seats.
And we always had a bunch of old coats laying over them.
And somebody would create a little diversion when the ticket takers came along just to get them.
moving on.
Did y'all ever suspect that probably the ticket taker knew what was happening?
Oh yes, yes.
We thought we were real smart.
Most of the cases they knew.
They could read us better than we could read them.
Alright, so you went up there.
Did the train stay there?
Did y'all get to sleep on the train?
No, we never slept on the train.
Where would you spend the night?
Well, somebody would have a hotel room.
And about 30 of us would spend the night.
We'd sleep on the floors.
And in most cases, however, we all had friends from either Dallas or Fort Warner or Houston or Waco.
And in most cases, we were invited to spend the night at these friends' houses.
So you did two of those a year.
Yeah.
Which was your favorite town?
Well, since I was from Greenville, I enjoyed Dallas more than any.

Fort Worth was a little rougher because the people at Fort Worth, some of the people at Fort Worth in the nightclubs where we used to go were a little rougher than the ones in Dallas and some of our boys got beat up pretty bad in fights up there at Fort Worth.
But I enjoyed Dallas the best and I guess Houston next and then Fort Worth and then Wake up.
Austin.
I never did, I went to Austin for the 1940 game when we got beat, when we were supposed to go to the Rose Bowl.
Then in 41, fall of 41 we played here.
I didn't go to too many of those portraits in Austin.
The, did you see much of those famous Aggie footballers?
on campus?
Were they?
I saw them all the time.
Who were your favorites as people?
As people?
Well, I admired and I thought a great deal of John Kimball.
I had a little argument
a few days ago, maybe you were bothered about John Kimball.
Somebody said he wasn't a very good student.
No, no, no.
I said, I don't think that's so.
They said, oh, everybody had to help him go through.
And I said, well, I sat in chemistry class with John, and he didn't have any trouble whatsoever.
He was a principal fellow.
That's what I heard.
And I knew Tommy Baum very well.
He was kind of a wild monkey, but a hell of a good guy.
Howard Shelton, who was my company commander, was an electrical engineering student, and a member of the Scholarship Honor Society, and played football.
And there's Cullen Rogers, who was in A Company, and then later on, close to him, and I knew
Martin Ruby, and I knew Jim Sterling.
I knew Roy Bluchek.
I knew Darius Mosier.
I knew Bill Panacher.
I was in summer camp at Camp Willis in San Antonio with Bill Panacher.
Matter of fact, I rode home with him when he went from
San Antonio to Denison.
He was from Denison.
Denison, yellow jacket.
Yeah, and he let me out in Dallas and I caught a ride some way to Greenville.
But I was, we all were close.
That football team was very popular among the students and they weren't standoffish.
Where did the athletes live then?
Well, earlier they lived in Walden Hall.
But then when they built the new dorms,
They moved in dorm 12.
The band was in dorm 11.
Duncan Hall in the middle, dorm 12 over here, and the football players were there.
Of all the student leadership positions when you were a student, which ones carried the most prestige?
The cadet colonel.
The cadet colonel was the number one student of the corps and the student body.
The second was probably the president of the senior class.
And then it probably went to the regimental command, like the top man in the infantry, the top man in the artillery, the top man in the coast, the top man in the capital.
Band was highly regarded?
Band was highly regarded.
The commanders of the band, they had an infantry band, an artillery band, and a total band commander.
They were highly respected and considered leaders.
Did y'all have a nickname for the band?
No, just the Aggie band.
They had a, what they called it, a white band and a maroon band.
And one was the artillery and one was the infantry.
And it was about 200 pieces or a little less and a pretty good band.
Did y'all think then of them as being very, very good at their marching routine of games?
We thought they were the best in the world.
We were proud of them.
We were proud of the Ross Volunteers.
We thought they were a neat outfit, though it was not a large organization.
We were proud of them.
Were there singing cadets then?
Yes.
Were they called that?
Yes, they were called singing cadets.
Mr. Joe Lookit was the head of the singing cadets.
And Buck Weiris was a part member of the singing cadets.
That's what was Pete Adams, my friend, who got killed in Brian.
And we felt like they were very, very good.
We're getting near the end now.
What creates Aggie spirit?
What creates Aggie pride?
I think what you run into on the campus, what you see that happens on the campus day and night.
You see things done that you wouldn't expect and you have a great appreciation for the fact that it happened that way.
And it therefore creates a spirit, a feeling.
Are there any events that are key to that?
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
The band as it plays.
the marches, the silver taps, the mustard, all add factors to that.
But I think that the spirit, the actual spirit comes with the basic fundamental of how you were treated and how you were respected and how you were handled while you were on the campus.
Were you mistreated?
When you needed help, were you assisted?
Did your faculty, did your teachers laugh at you or did they help you?
When you needed help, who'd you go to and how did they meet your problem?
And those little things that you

probably I you know if I had to sit down and write what what the Aggie spirit is I couldn't think of the damn thing but I'm sure maybe but I think it's just a combination of all those things to the point when it was all over it was there I mean it was there and it just gave you a feeling that well this has been such a wonderful experience I hope it'll last for eternity
And I hope that I'll be able to do something to kind of repay.
Okay, that's the next question.
Yeah.
Let's make believe that somebody gives you a million dollars.
Yeah.
And the only condition is you've got to give it to A&M and you decide what's going to be done with it.
Yeah.
What would you want it done with?
Where would it, what area or what?
Well, I think I would not give it for anything physical.
I think if I could, I would say I want this for scholarships.
Any particular thing?
Not any.
I don't have any right now.
I wouldn't want to particularly restrict it to...
in any particular field, I think I would want to say, I want you to give this scholarship to somebody who meets certain criteria, one of which would be a need.
I wouldn't want a scholarship to go to a boy or girl, I wouldn't restrict it to a boy.
A boy or a girl, whatever agenda or whatever color, I wouldn't care.
But somebody who needed it, but on the other side, somebody who could make it.
But some little help, you know.
And then I might want to set up an award for a teacher.
And I wouldn't care what field of teacher.
I would think I would want one that would be recognized for his student relationships.
I would want to recognize a teacher not because he was the best biochemist in the world, but because he did more for students than anybody else.
And so that's what I do.
Next to last.
What did it mean to you in your life that you went here instead of somewhere else?
Everything.
Everything.
I could, like I say, I could have gone to Texas Tech and I think I could have gone to University of Texas.
I graduated with a pretty high honors up in Greenville and I could have gotten into any school I guess in Texas.
But I just had a desire to come to this school and never regretted it one bit of one single time.
And it's just meant everything to me.
And I mean no disrespect to the other institutions, because I'm a believer of higher education, wherever it comes from.
But this school, and I think really the thing that makes me feel so strong to the institution, for the fact that I, all of them,
And I'm not talking about just the classroom teacher.
I'm talking about the people in the dining hall.
I'm talking about the wives of the faculty that I came to know.
And I'm talking about the administrators, the staff, the deans, the student relationship people, the TAC officers, the people that worked in the
in the buildings.
Just everybody around here seemed to have a feeling about being helpful to me.
And those were important to me.
I can't answer your question.
I don't know.
The last question is almost repetitive.
What feelings do you have in your heart for Indiana?
Oh, super.
Super.
I think so much for it that I worry about it.
I want it to be as good as I think it was at the base.
And I'm not sure it's as good as it was.
But I don't mean to say that I'm not highly supportive of the administration and what's been done.
I think the girls, I think it was time to bring the girls in.
I think they deserved it.
I think it was time to let the blacks come in.
They could make it more power to them.
I think it was time that this corps be optional.
You either be in the corps or you don't.
If you want to go the fraternity route, go ahead.
If you want to do something else, go ahead.
But I just think, now sometimes, to be honest, I think we do some bad, good things.
But I don't make a case out of it.
But I don't let those things bother me.
Let's quit there.
Let's go.
